<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n11124a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n11" href="#n11124a">N11 (VI.B.5)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n11all.htm#n11124a"> 124(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> leagues (not miles)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>Le Chol&eacute;ra</b> Le chol&eacute;ra, sorti du Delta du Gange en 1817, s&apos;est propag&eacute; dans un espace de deux mille deux cents lieues, du nord au sud, et de trois mille cinq cents de l&apos;orient &agrave; l&apos;occident; il a d&eacute;sol&eacute; quatorze cents villes, moissonn&eacute; quarante millions d&apos;individus. On a une carte de la marche de ce conqu&eacute;rant. Il a mis quinze ann&eacute;es &agrave; venir de l&apos;Inde &agrave; Paris: c&apos;est aller aussi vite que Bonaparte: celui-ci employa &agrave; peu pr&egrave;s le m&ecirc;me nombre d&apos;ann&eacute;es &agrave; passer de Cadix &agrave; Moscou, et il n&apos;a fait p&eacute;rir que deux ou trois millions d&apos;hommes. <br><font color="green">[Cholera, issuing from the Ganges Delta in 1817, spread across a space of 2,200 <mark>leagues</mark>, from north to south, and 3,500 from east to west. It devastated fourteen hundred towns, harvesting forty million people. There is a map showing this conqueror&apos;s march. It took fifteen years to come from India to Paris, which means travelling as quickly as Bonaparte. The latter took almost exactly the same number of years to pass from Cadiz to Moscow, and he brought about the death of only two or three million men.]</font> <small> Chateaubriand, <a name="CHBD" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CHBD"><cite title="source">&OElig;uvres choisies illustr&eacute;es</cite></a> (1912) III, <i> M&eacute;moires d&apos;Outre-tombe.</i> 159</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
